english:
  title: A Farewell Letter for Han Yu-mun, the New Presented Scholar
  author: Kwon Keun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Han Yu-mun came to visit me through his mentor Jung-jil, seeking instruction in the Book of Documents. With each passing season, his reverence deepened and his learning flourished. The following spring, when Master Yi of To-eun presided over the state examination with meticulous scrutiny of all compositions, Han Yu-mun achieved the highest distinction. Preparing to return to Chingju to honor his parents, the National University masters and scholars—led by Kim Kong of the Yak-jae school—composed poems to celebrate his journey.

    Before departing, Han Yu-mun bade me farewell, saying: "I have studied under your guidance for two years now. That I have been selected and can bring honor to my parents is entirely your gift. Yet what my parents hope for me, and what I wish to learn from you, extends far beyond this moment. Now I must travel far and can no longer attend upon you daily to hear your teachings. I humbly ask that you leave me with one final word of instruction."

    I replied: "You learned the Book of Documents from me—how could anything I say to you lie outside its pages? Long ago, our sage Confucius answered a question thus: 'The Classic says, practice filial piety, honor your elder brothers, and apply this to governing the realm.' Mencius likewise answered Cao Jiao: 'The way of Yao and Shun is simply filial piety and fraternal love.' How penetrating is the sage's teaching!

    Now, the Book of Documents speaks of how kings govern—it may seem distant from a scholar's own life. Yet all its teachings derive from filial piety and brotherly love. When Yao brought harmony to the nine kinship circles, when Shun gradually rectified all things and evil found no foothold—these were the perfection of filial and fraternal devotion. The way of the sages of the three dynasties never departed from this principle. Is this not simply the fulfillment of our nature?

    When you rest from serving your parents, take this thought and seek it in the records of the four ancient dynasties. The ways of Yao, Shun, Yu, and Tang; the accomplishments of Gao, Kui, Yi, and Fu; the deeds of Zhou and Shao—none of these fail to speak directly to self-cultivation. If you would be filial, emulate Shun's service to his blind father. If you would be a devoted brother, follow Zhou Gong's reverence toward King Wu. Through study and understanding, through diligent practice and persistent effort, extend these principles until all things, all matters find their proper fulfillment.

    Ah, what you perfect in yourself flows forth to others. What you establish in your household reaches the realm. When you one day take up the work of governance, is its foundation not already here? Go forth with resolve.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Book of Documents' (Shangshu/상서) was one of the Confucian classics, believed to contain the words and deeds of ancient sage-kings. It was a standard text for civil service examination candidates.
    - Han Yu-mun's achieving 'high distinction' (高選) in the state examination was a significant achievement that would lead to official position and bring honor to his family.
    - The references to Yao, Shun, Yu, Tang, Kings Wen and Wu, and their ministers (Gao, Kui, Yi Fu, Zhou, and Shao) invoke the archetypal models of sage-rulers and virtuous ministers in Confucian tradition.
